 "photo_credit": "via Wikimedia Commons (CC BY-SA)",
 "blurb": "The bouncing-on-his-heels arena observationalist — the man who turned the contents of every British man's kitchen drawer into a sold-out Wembley bit.",
 "bio": "Michael McIntyre is the rare comic whose entire act is built from premises so obvious they sound like they couldn't possibly hold an arena, until he sells out 10 nights at the O2 with them anyway. He works the small stuff with full physical commitment: the man-drawer of broken keys and dead batteries; the way British people pretend to know the words to the National Anthem; how every parent secretly hates Frozen; the weird theater of saying 'I'll let you go' on the phone. In 2012 he was the highest-grossing stand-up in the world. He started in clubs in 1999, became a household name on Live at the Apollo in 2007–09, and now anchors BBC One Saturday nights with Michael McIntyre's Big Show, the kind of post-Morecambe-and-Wise variety perch British comedy almost never produces anymore.",
 "links": {
